<h1>RAVIOLI</h2>
<img src="C:\Users\malkb\OneDrive\Desktop\malek.dev\projects\recipes\recipes\download.jpg" />
<h2>Description</h2>
<p>Ravioli is a type of Italian pasta consisting of small, square or circular pockets of dough filled with various ingredients such as cheese, meat, vegetables, or a combination of these. The dough is typically made from flour and eggs, and the filling can vary widely, offering a diverse range of flavors and textures. Ravioli is commonly served boiled or in soups, and it is often accompanied by a variety of sauces, such as marinara, pesto, or brown butter with sage.</p>
<h3>Ingredients</h3>
<ul><li>"All-purpose flour"<li><li>"Eggs"<li><li>"Salt"<li><li>"Cheese (such as ricotta, Parmesan, or mozzarella)"<li><li>"Meat (such as ground beef, pork, or sausage) for meat-filled ravioli"<li><li>"Vegetables (like spinach or butternut squash) for vegetarian options"<li><li>"Marinara sauce"<li><li>"Brown butter and sage"<li></ul>
<h4>Instruction</h4>
<p>1. Make the Dough:
a. On a clean surface, create a mound with the flour and make a well in the center.
b. Crack the eggs into the well and add a pinch of salt.
c. Using a fork, gradually incorporate the flour into the eggs until a dough forms.
d. Knead the dough for about 8-10 minutes until it becomes smooth and elastic. Add water if needed to achieve the right consistency.
e. Wrap the dough in plastic wrap and let it rest for at least 30 minutes.

2. Prepare the Filling:
a. In a bowl, combine the ricotta and Parmesan cheese.
b. Season with salt, pepper, and any additional flavorings like minced garlic or herbs.
c. Mix well until the filling is smooth and well combined.

3. Roll Out the Dough:
a. Divide the rested dough into smaller portions.
b. Roll out each portion into thin sheets, either using a rolling pin or a pasta machine.

4. Assemble the Ravioli:
a. Place small dollops of the cheese filling on one sheet of rolled-out dough, leaving enough space between each filling.
b. Brush water around the edges of the dough to help seal the ravioli.
c. Place a second sheet of rolled-out dough on top and press around each mound of filling to seal the edges.

5. Cut and Seal:
a. Use a ravioli cutter or a knife to cut out individual ravioli.
b. Press the edges firmly to seal each ravioli, ensuring there are no air pockets.

6. Cook the Ravioli:
a. Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil.
b. Carefully drop the ravioli into the boiling water and cook for 2-4 minutes or until they float to the surface.</p>

